The conditional type has no reason to work on a tuple, your conditional type basically resolves to the question `[typeof Position, typeof Status] extends Attribute&lt;infer T&gt;` which it clearly does not so you end up with never.

You could pass in a union into the type (`AttributeTypes&lt;typeof Position | typeof Status&gt;`) and then you will get `Position[] | Status[]` which is not really what you want ([Play](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play/#))

You could also use an array in your conditional type (`Attributes extends Array&lt;Attribute&lt;infer T&gt;&gt; ? T[] : never`) but that will not preserve the tuple structure in the input ([Play](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play/#-EFBDdxnsDk8inBgMFsmEFFSaZMqm8sXgNEA))


The best way to get the output you want is to use a mapped type. Mapped types preserve tuple while allowing you to map every element type of a tuple to a new element type in the resulting tuple:

```ts
type Attribute&lt;Type&gt; = { id: string, type?: Type };

type Position = { x: number, y: number };
let Position: Attribute&lt;Position&gt; = { id: &quot;position&quot; };

type Status = &quot;active&quot; | &quot;inactive&quot;;
let Status: Attribute&lt;Status&gt; = { id: &quot;status&quot; };

type AttributeTypes&lt;Attributes extends Attribute&lt;any&gt;[]&gt; = {
  [P in keyof Attributes]: Attributes[P] extends Attribute&lt;infer T&gt; ? T : never;
}

type Result = AttributeTypes&lt;[typeof Position, typeof Status]&gt; // is [Position, Status]
```
[Play](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play/#code/GYVwdgxgLglg9mABAZwBQEpEG8BQjFQCeADgKaICCUUATjAEYhSkA8AKiaQHyIC82iGABMAXClowwAcwA0BTgH4xHMogC+Abhx55qgApxkMWAj4CAHmLAgAtvVI05hK7fs11W-ABtSURAaMTMDEqCUZmFgDjeDAefixBUUQAImJDaIRkj218IlUAZSgAQygQZDNkougYADdSLIAfFMkq2Drkz0QfP0KSspDqOnDWXtLkOIFhMWTkYrGszRzdclChplIVUmQWVYZ18tJzZjAhct3hliKwQi4AbQBdCdx8fFu9QSQAa1JCOGBKQZ7ZjIe4DML7N73RCHY6nAHgiKSYAORBsHgKVGIKykOo0TpqJZ5cgAJS2IC8fn453Wm22tyJf386SCcgZ-1GZUeiBwaiAA)

